word as it makes us feel like we almost have the word right in front of us. This experience demonstrates the partial retrieval of information from the brain, like the word's meaning and abstract form like the first syllable, but not the whole complete word. ASL also has this phenomenon known as the tip of the finger. Other than the tip of the tongue phenomenon, there are also many other examples and experiments done in psycholinguistics like determining how words for "nose" from different languages are formulated with a nasal sound. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c References: %0a%3c https://theconversation.com/what-brain-regions-control-our-language-and-how-do-we-know-this-63318%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.thoughtco.com/tipofthetongue-tot-phenomenon-1692548#:~:text=In%2520psycholinguistics%252C%2520the%2520tip%252Dof,with%2520uncommon%2520words%2520and%2520names.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
